<div class="page-body">
  <div class="content-grid">

    <!-- MAIN COLUMN -->
    <div class="main-col">
      <div class="section-bar">This Week's Summary</div>
      <div class="summary-block">This week's incidents reveal K-12 cybersecurity continues to deteriorate, with new data showing half of all U.S. districts experienced incidents in 2025 and ransomware compromising nearly 4 million education records. Districts now face specific compliance gaps: only 11% have formal AI vetting processes despite widespread AI adoption, and a California vendor case exposes how routine event access tools can violate state privacy law. The common thread is not awareness but action: knowing risks exist without implementing documented review processes.</div>

      <div class="section-bar dark-bar">Incidents</div>
      
      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-header">
          <div class="incident-num">1</div>
          <div class="incident-title-block">
            <div class="incident-title">California vendor PlayOn violated state privacy law by collecting student data for prom and football game access</div>
            <div class="incident-source">edhat &middot; March 15, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="field-label">What happened</div><div class="incident-field">PlayOn, contracted with roughly 1,400 California schools, repeatedly violated state privacy law in 2023 and 2024 by requiring students to provide personal information to attend school events like prom and football games. The violations were systematic, not isolated incidents. This case demonstrates how vendors providing seemingly low-risk services can fail compliance requirements.</div>
        <div class="field-label">Who's affected</div><div class="incident-field">All California districts using PlayOn or similar event ticketing and access control vendors. Districts in other states using platforms that gate event access behind data collection forms.</div>
        <div class="field-label red">Compliance Exposure</div><div class="incident-field">FERPA and state privacy law violations if districts did not document that PlayOn's data collection was educationally necessary and that a data sharing agreement limited collection to the minimum required. A federal monitor would look for: signed data processing agreements, documentation of the educational purpose for collecting data to access school events, and evidence that alternatives were considered. If districts cannot produce these records, they may face findings that they failed to protect student privacy.</div>
        <div class="action-box"><div class="action-label">Recommended Action</div>Inventory all vendors that collect student data for non-instructional purposes (events, athletics, activities). Verify a signed data sharing agreement exists for each, that it limits collection to minimum necessary data, and that it specifies how data is stored and deleted. If any vendor lacks this documentation, suspend data sharing and require legal review before reinstating access.</div>
        <div class="workflow-tag"><div class="workflow-label">Workflow Impact</div>Vendor Management: Audit event access and extracurricular activity platforms for data collection practices and signed agreements</div>
      </div>
      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-header">
          <div class="incident-num">2</div>
          <div class="incident-title-block">
            <div class="incident-title">Los Angeles classroom incident exposes inadequacy of state AI guidance after sexualized images appeared</div>
            <div class="incident-source">Westside Current &middot; March 11, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="field-label">What happened</div><div class="incident-field">An AI tool generated sexualized images during classroom use in Los Angeles Unified School District, prompting criticism that state AI guidance and district policies are insufficient to protect students. The incident occurred despite existing guidance, revealing a gap between policy documents and operational safeguards. This is not a theoretical risk but a documented classroom failure.</div>
        <div class="field-label">Who's affected</div><div class="incident-field">All districts using AI tools accessible to students, particularly generative AI platforms that create images or respond to open-ended prompts. High risk for districts without content filtering or monitoring of AI tool outputs.</div>
        <div class="field-label red">Compliance Exposure</div><div class="incident-field">Title IX requires districts to maintain an environment free from sexual harassment, which includes addressing sexually explicit materials in classrooms regardless of source. A federal review would examine whether the district had documented procedures to prevent inappropriate AI-generated content, whether staff were trained on these procedures, and whether the district took immediate corrective action. Absent documentation, the district may face findings that it failed to supervise instructional technology or protect students from a sexually hostile environment.</div>
        <div class="action-box"><div class="action-label">Recommended Action</div>Review all AI tools accessible to students for content filtering capabilities. Document what filtering exists, what types of prompts are blocked, and who monitors outputs. If a tool lacks content filtering or monitoring, either implement technical controls (such as supervised use only, prompt review, or API-level filtering) or remove student access until controls are in place. Ensure incident response procedures explicitly address inappropriate AI outputs.</div>
        <div class="workflow-tag"><div class="workflow-label">Workflow Impact</div>Instructional Technology: Audit AI tool content filtering and establish documented monitoring procedures for student-facing generative AI</div>
      </div>
      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-header">
          <div class="incident-num">3</div>
          <div class="incident-title-block">
            <div class="incident-title">Real-time monitoring data reveals students used ChatGPT to ask how to commit suicide</div>
            <div class="incident-source">Education Week &middot; March 11, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="field-label">What happened</div><div class="incident-field">New monitoring tools show K-12 students are using AI on school devices for concerning purposes, including asking ChatGPT how to commit suicide. Data also shows students use ChatGPT more often than AI tools designed for K-12 settings. This is not speculation about potential misuse but documented evidence of harmful queries on school networks.</div>
        <div class="field-label">Who's affected</div><div class="incident-field">All districts where students can access ChatGPT or similar general-purpose AI tools on school devices or networks. Particularly critical for districts that have not restricted or monitored AI tool access.</div>
        <div class="field-label red">Compliance Exposure</div><div class="incident-field">Districts have a duty to supervise student technology use and respond to known risks of self-harm. If a district is aware that students are using school devices to research suicide methods and does not implement filtering, monitoring, or intervention protocols, it may face liability if a student is harmed. A federal review would look for: documented acceptable use policies that address AI tools, technical controls that restrict access to high-risk platforms, and evidence that staff are trained to recognize and respond to warning signs. Failure to document these measures creates legal exposure.</div>
        <div class="action-box"><div class="action-label">Recommended Action</div>Immediately verify whether ChatGPT and similar general-purpose AI tools are accessible on school networks and devices. If accessible, implement content filtering to block or flag high-risk queries (self-harm, violence, explicit content). Ensure monitoring systems alert counselors or administrators to concerning searches. Document the technical controls in place and train staff on response protocols. If monitoring reveals concerning queries, follow existing crisis intervention procedures and document the response.</div>
        <div class="workflow-tag"><div class="workflow-label">Workflow Impact</div>Security &amp; Infrastructure: Implement AI tool access controls and monitoring with alerts for high-risk student queries</div>
      </div>
      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-header">
          <div class="incident-num">4</div>
          <div class="incident-title-block">
            <div class="incident-title">Half of U.S. school districts experienced a cybersecurity incident in 2025, yet only 11% vet AI tools for security risk</div>
            <div class="incident-source">PR Newswire &middot; March 12, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="field-label">What happened</div><div class="incident-field">A new report reveals 50% of U.S. school districts experienced a cybersecurity incident in 2025. Four out of five districts believe AI is increasing cybersecurity risk, but only 11% have formal processes to vet AI use in edtech tools. This creates a documented gap: districts recognize the risk but have not implemented the review processes federal auditors expect to see.</div>
        <div class="field-label">Who's affected</div><div class="incident-field">All districts, particularly those that have adopted AI-enabled tools without formal vetting. This affects vendor risk management for any tool with AI features: student information systems, learning platforms, chatbots, analytics tools, and administrative software.</div>
        <div class="field-label red">Compliance Exposure</div><div class="incident-field">FERPA requires districts to use reasonable methods to ensure vendors protect student data. If a district adopts AI-enabled tools without documented security vetting, it may fail this standard. A federal audit would look for: a vendor vetting process that explicitly addresses AI capabilities, documentation that security questions were asked before contract signature, and evidence that AI features were evaluated for data exposure risks. An 11% compliance rate means 89% of districts may lack the documentation needed to demonstrate reasonable methods.</div>
        <div class="action-box"><div class="action-label">Recommended Action</div>Establish a documented AI vetting process this week. At minimum, create a checklist that asks: Does this tool use AI? What data does the AI process? Where is data stored and processed? Is data used to train models? What security certifications does the vendor hold? Require this checklist be completed and retained for all new technology purchases. For existing AI-enabled tools, prioritize vetting any tool that processes student data and document the review even if the tool remains in use.</div>
        <div class="workflow-tag"><div class="workflow-label">Workflow Impact</div>Vendor Management: Establish formal AI vetting checklist and apply it to all new edtech purchases and existing AI-enabled tools</div>
      </div>
      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-header">
          <div class="incident-num">5</div>
          <div class="incident-title-block">
            <div class="incident-title">Ransomware gangs compromised 3.89 million U.S. education records, over 98% of all breached education data</div>
            <div class="incident-source">District Administration &middot; March 14, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="field-label">What happened</div><div class="incident-field">Attacks on U.S. schools decreased slightly, but ransomware gangs successfully infiltrated 3.89 million education records, representing more than 98% of all compromised educational records. This is not about attack volume but attack success: when breaches occur, they are nearly always ransomware, and they are nearly always catastrophic in scale. The concentration of damage in ransomware attacks signals where districts must focus defenses.</div>
        <div class="field-label">Who's affected</div><div class="incident-field">All districts, but highest risk for districts that lack multi-factor authentication on administrative systems, do not segment networks to isolate student data, or have not tested incident response plans. The statistic shows ransomware is not a theoretical risk but the dominant breach mechanism.</div>
        <div class="field-label red">Compliance Exposure</div><div class="incident-field">FERPA requires districts to protect student records from unauthorized disclosure. If a ransomware attack exfiltrates student data and the district cannot demonstrate it implemented reasonable security measures, it may face findings that it failed its statutory duty. A federal review would examine: whether multi-factor authentication was required for systems containing student data, whether networks were segmented to limit breach scope, whether backups were isolated from production systems, and whether the district tested its incident response plan. Absent documentation of these controls, a district may be found to have failed reasonable security standards.</div>
        <div class="action-box"><div class="action-label">Recommended Action</div>Verify immediately whether multi-factor authentication is required for all accounts that access student information systems. If not, implement MFA as an emergency priority, no exceptions. Document the date MFA was enabled and which systems are covered. Review network segmentation: can an attacker who compromises one system access student databases? If yes, document a plan to segment networks and set a completion deadline. Schedule a tabletop exercise of the district's ransomware response plan within 30 days and document the exercise and any gaps identified.</div>
        <div class="workflow-tag"><div class="workflow-label">Workflow Impact</div>Security &amp; Infrastructure: Audit MFA implementation on student data systems and document network segmentation plan</div>
      </div>

      
      <div class="section-bar" style="margin-top:32px;">References</div>
      <div class="references-section">
        <div class="references"><div class="ref-incident-title">California vendor PlayOn violated state privacy law by collecting student data for prom and football game access</div><div class="ref-citation">[1] edhat. &ldquo;To Attend Prom or a Football Game, California Students First Had to Surrender Their Data.&rdquo; March 15, 2026. <a href="https://www.edhat.com/california/news/to-attend-prom-or-a-football-game-california-students-first-had-to-surrender-their-data/">https://www.edhat.com/california/news/to-attend-prom-or-a-football-game-california-students-first-had-to-surrender-their-data/</a></div><div class="ref-incident-title">Los Angeles classroom incident exposes inadequacy of state AI guidance after sexualized images appeared</div><div class="ref-citation">[1] Westside Current. &ldquo;State AI Guidance Under Fire After Sexualized Images Hit LA Classroom.&rdquo; March 11, 2026. <a href="https://www.westsidecurrent.com/news/state-ai-guidance-under-fire-after-sexualized-images-hit-la-classroom/article_3089da37-0558-4664-9ccf-2c57b8b38f0c.html">https://www.westsidecurrent.com/news/state-ai-guidance-under-fire-after-sexualized-images-hit-la-classroom/article_3089da37-0558-4664-9ccf-2c57b8b38f0c.html</a></div><div class="ref-incident-title">Real-time monitoring data reveals students used ChatGPT to ask how to commit suicide</div><div class="ref-citation">[1] Education Week. &ldquo;Real-Time Data Shows Exactly How Students Use AI on School Technology.&rdquo; March 11, 2026. <a href="https://www.edweek.org/technology/real-time-data-shows-exactly-how-students-use-ai-on-school-technology/2026/03">https://www.edweek.org/technology/real-time-data-shows-exactly-how-students-use-ai-on-school-technology/2026/03</a></div><div class="ref-incident-title">Half of U.S. school districts experienced a cybersecurity incident in 2025, yet only 11% vet AI tools for security risk</div><div class="ref-citation">[1] PR Newswire. &ldquo;New Report Finds One in Two U.S. School Districts Experienced a Cybersecurity Incident in 2025.&rdquo; March 12, 2026. <a href="https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-report-finds-one-in-two-us-school-districts-experienced-a-cybersecurity-incident-in-2025-302709821.html">https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-report-finds-one-in-two-us-school-districts-experienced-a-cybersecurity-incident-in-2025-302709821.html</a></div><div class="ref-incident-title">Ransomware gangs compromised 3.89 million U.S. education records, over 98% of all breached education data</div><div class="ref-citation">[1] District Administration. &ldquo;Ransomware Data Breaches Soar in the U.S., Affecting K12 and Higher Ed Privacy.&rdquo; March 14, 2026. <a href="https://districtadministration.com/article/ransomware-data-breaches-soar-in-the-u-s-affecting-k12-and-higher-ed-privacy/">https://districtadministration.com/article/ransomware-data-breaches-soar-in-the-u-s-affecting-k12-and-higher-ed-privacy/</a></div></div>
      </div>
