    <!-- SIDEBAR -->
    <div class="sidebar">
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-number">Only 11% of school districts have formal processes to vet AI use in edtech tools</div><div class="stat-label">By the Numbers</div><div class="stat-context">This means 89% of districts may lack the documented vendor review process federal auditors expect when evaluating whether a district used reasonable methods to ensure vendors protect student data under FERPA.</div><div class="stat-source">PR Newswire, March 12, 2026</div></div>
      <div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card-title">Policy Watch</div><div class="policy-item"><div>California is positioning itself as the de facto national regulator for AI in children's products following the January 2026 announcement of the Parents &amp; Kids Safe AI Act ballot initiative, an alliance between OpenAI and Common Sense Media. The initiative would establish statewide AI safety standards for products used by children, with implications extending beyond California because major edtech vendors typically build to the most restrictive state standard rather than maintain multiple product versions. This creates a national compliance floor even for districts outside California.</div><div class="policy-action">No action required yet. Monitor the initiative's progress and language. If it qualifies for the ballot and polls favorably, begin reviewing whether your current AI-enabled tools would meet California's proposed standards, as vendors may begin implementing changes in advance of any effective date.</div></div><div class="policy-item"><div>Seventeen states filed a lawsuit in March 2026 to block a Trump administration mandate requiring colleges to report detailed admissions data on race, gender, and test scores, arguing it violates student privacy laws. While the lawsuit targets higher education, it raises questions about the scope of FERPA protections and whether similar federal data collection mandates could extend to K-12. The case may establish precedent on the limits of federal authority to compel disclosure of individually identifiable education records.</div><div class="policy-action">No action required yet. The lawsuit is in early stages. K-12 districts should note the privacy arguments being raised and be prepared to respond if similar federal reporting mandates are proposed for K-12 data.</div></div></div>
      <div class="sidebar-card"><div class="sidebar-card-title">Tool Alerts</div><div class="tool-row"><span class="tool-name">PlayOn (event ticketing and access)</span><span class="tool-change">Under scrutiny for systematic California state privacy law violations in 2023-2024. Districts using PlayOn or similar event access platforms should verify data sharing agreements explicitly limit data collection to minimum necessary and document the educational purpose for collecting data to access school events.</span></div><div class="tool-row"><span class="tool-name">Adobe AI (generative image tools)</span><span class="tool-change">Generated sexualized images in a Los Angeles elementary classroom in March 2026, exposing inadequate content filtering for K-12 use. Districts using Adobe AI tools accessible to students should verify content filtering settings and implement supervised use protocols.</span></div><div class="tool-row"><span class="tool-name">ChatGPT (general-purpose AI)</span><span class="tool-change">Monitoring data shows K-12 students use ChatGPT on school devices more often than AI tools designed for education, including documented queries about self-harm. Districts should verify whether ChatGPT is accessible on school networks and implement filtering or monitoring if it is.</span></div></div>
